As Eti mentioned, we're going to be using pancreatic cancer as an example to talk

27
00:01:32.020 --> 00:01:35.660
about molecular and cellular alterations in precancers.

28
00:01:36.260 --> 00:01:37.440
I have no disclosures.

29
00:01:39.080 --> 00:01:41.660
So since I'm the first speaker, I wanted to just start by giving some of the

30
00:01:41.680 --> 00:01:45.040
background of why pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma, or PDAC, is an important

31
00:01:45.060 --> 00:01:48.940
disease to study. Probably everybody in the room knows that it has a dismal

32
00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:49.680
survival rate,

33
00:01:50.960 --> 00:01:54.880
partly due to late detection, but it highlights that

34
00:01:54.900 --> 00:01:57.280
there's important opportunities for prevention and interception.

35
00:01:57.320 --> 00:02:01.100
And I think one of the big focuses in my lab is leveraging human tissue samples to

36
00:02:01.140 --> 00:02:01.960
meet these goals.

37
00:02:02.840 --> 00:02:05.880
And the way that we think about it is if we want to do data-driven interception, we

38
00:02:05.920 --> 00:02:08.680
need to understand precancers, how they occur in humans.

39
00:02:11.021 --> 00:02:14.460
So again, as the first talk, I thought I would level set a bit and introduce the

40
00:02:14.480 --> 00:02:16.400
two different types of precancers in the pancreas.

41
00:02:16.460 --> 00:02:19.460
So the majority, about 90% of pancreatic cancers, arise through

42
00:02:19.560 --> 00:02:22.160
microscopic precancerous lesions.

43
00:02:22.560 --> 00:02:25.480
These are called pancreatic intraepithelial neoplasia or PanIN.

44
00:02:25.940 --> 00:02:29.000
These are by definition less than five millimeters, which means they can't be seen

45
00:02:29.040 --> 00:02:32.180
on traditional imaging studies. They also can't be seen in grossly

46
00:02:32.880 --> 00:02:35.260
resected pancreas specimens if you're looking with the naked eye.

47
00:02:35.660 --> 00:02:36.740
Makes them challenging to study.

48
00:02:37.760 --> 00:02:41.440
PanINs are graded based on the morphologic features of their epithelium into

49
00:02:41.520 --> 00:02:44.540
low-grade with minimal atypia, and then high-grade, thought to be the step

50
00:02:44.580 --> 00:02:46.380
immediately prior to invasive carcinoma.

51
00:02:47.420 --> 00:02:51.220
An important minority of pancreatic cancers, again, somewhere between 10 and 15%,

52
00:02:51.380 --> 00:02:53.240
arise through larger cystic precancers.

53
00:02:53.680 --> 00:02:57.010
The most common one of these is intraductal papillary mucinous neoplasm or

54
00:02:57.060 --> 00:03:01.020
IPMN. These are by definition greater than a centimeter, but they can get much

55
00:03:01.100 --> 00:03:04.600
larger. This means they can be identified on imaging.

56
00:03:04.700 --> 00:03:08.060
They can also be identified in a grossly resected pancreas specimen if you want to

57
00:03:08.080 --> 00:03:11.860
harvest tissue for research. It makes them easier to study, but also creates

58
00:03:11.900 --> 00:03:15.760
clinical conundrums in that they're often identified incidentally, and we have

59
00:03:15.800 --> 00:03:19.700
to decide who needs a resection to prevent pancreatic cancer versus who can be

60
00:03:19.720 --> 00:03:20.460
safely watched.

61
00:03:21.520 --> 00:03:25.400
IPMNs, like PanINs, are graded based on the morphology into low-grade and

62
00:03:25.460 --> 00:03:25.960
high-grade.

63
00:03:28.400 --> 00:03:30.640
So when I first started my group several years ago,

64
00:03:31.820 --> 00:03:35.040
we focused a lot on IPMNs because of their larger size and convenience to study,

65
00:03:35.160 --> 00:03:38.820
but obviously if 90% of pancreatic cancers arise through PanINs, we

66
00:03:38.880 --> 00:03:42.760
ignore them at our peril. So we'll start by talking about IPMNs, and then we'll

67
00:03:42.800 --> 00:03:43.820
switch over to PanINs.

68
00:03:46.180 --> 00:03:49.940
So anyone in this audience who knows me knows that I do a lot of neoplastic cell

69
00:03:49.980 --> 00:03:53.800
focused work, looking at genomics and other neoplastic cell alterations.

70
00:03:54.200 --> 00:03:55.860
So I will talk a little bit about that.

71
00:03:56.700 --> 00:03:59.440
When I first got the invitation from Eti to speak, I was a little surprised because

72
00:03:59.460 --> 00:04:02.960
we don't do a ton of stuff with stroma, but we do have some exciting unpublished

73
00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:06.410
recent data on IPMNs and stroma, so I'm excited to see what the group thinks about

74
00:04:06.440 --> 00:04:06.520
it.

75
00:04:08.320 --> 00:04:12.200
But I want to give a high-level overview of studies from

76
00:04:12.260 --> 00:04:16.240
over several years now, looking at multi-region genomic analysis and how

77
00:04:16.300 --> 00:04:18.380
it provides insights into precancer evolution.

78
00:04:19.899 --> 00:04:21.541
So the first is that IPMNs

79
00:04:22.680 --> 00:04:26.560
often have a polyclonal origin, so the initiating oncogenic

80
00:04:26.580 --> 00:04:29.880
mutation in IPMNs is usually either KRAS or VRG2.

81
00:04:30.320 --> 00:04:33.700
Low-grade IPMNs often have multiple mutations in one of these initiating

82
00:04:33.760 --> 00:04:37.140
mutations, and we've shown using more comprehensive sequencing that these really

83
00:04:37.180 --> 00:04:39.120
are independent clones within the same lesion.

84
00:04:39.760 --> 00:04:43.260
When an IPMN progresses, there's additional genetic alterations, and you have one

85
00:04:43.300 --> 00:04:47.260
of those clones that takes over. So the high-grade IPMNs are homogenous

86
00:04:47.300 --> 00:04:50.940
with respect to KRAS and VRG2, but then they have convergent evolution with respect

87
00:04:50.960 --> 00:04:52.360
to other driver gene mutations.

88
00:04:54.320 --> 00:04:58.000
We have lots of evidence over several years about multifocal neoplasia in

89
00:04:58.060 --> 00:05:01.660
IPMN patients. The first is that if somebody gets an

90
00:05:01.700 --> 00:05:04.960
IPMN that's surgically resected, they do have a risk of

91
00:05:05.440 --> 00:05:07.360
recurrence or progression in their remnant pancreas.

92
00:05:07.860 --> 00:05:11.460
And when this happens, if you genetically analyze both, the thing that comes back

93
00:05:11.500 --> 00:05:15.140
in the remnant is usually just a completely separate lesion, independent IPMN,

94
00:05:15.600 --> 00:05:18.480
sharing no genetic alterations with the thing that was originally resected.

95
00:05:18.980 --> 00:05:22.100
Really highlighting that it's a disease of the entire pancreas with multiple

96
00:05:22.360 --> 00:05:24.100
independent neoplasms spread throughout.

97
00:05:26.300 --> 00:05:30.260
When you have an IPMN with a carcinoma that's occurring at the

98
00:05:30.300 --> 00:05:34.120
same time, resected together, there is a small but substantial percentage of these

99
00:05:34.160 --> 00:05:38.100
that are, again, independent lesions, where the IPMN and the cancer

100
00:05:38.160 --> 00:05:41.400
in the same pancreas resected at the same time actually share no genetic

101
00:05:41.480 --> 00:05:42.200
alterations.

102
00:05:45.460 --> 00:05:46.440
When IPMNs, though,

103
00:05:47.460 --> 00:05:50.460
when they occur with cancers, most of the time they are related, and we've done

104
00:05:50.500 --> 00:05:53.180
really detailed genomic analysis and shown,

105
00:05:54.600 --> 00:05:57.980
I think quite definitively, that IPMNs can be precursors to invasive

106
00:05:58.020 --> 00:06:01.890
cancer.But one of the key questions, it's a

107
00:06:02.310 --> 00:06:06.130
major transition to go from an IPMN that is essentially curative surgically

108
00:06:06.170 --> 00:06:09.710
resected to an invasive cancer. What drives that transition?

109
00:06:09.980 --> 00:06:12.110
It's clinically very important.

110
00:06:13.090 --> 00:06:15.990
And we've shown that sometimes it can be driven by a somatic mutation.

111
00:06:16.090 --> 00:06:19.410
We did a study where we did whole exome sequencing of IPMN and adjacent

112
00:06:19.530 --> 00:06:22.760
cancer and showed that in, I think it was

113
00:06:23.970 --> 00:06:27.110
four cases, there were cancer-specific mutations that were in the

114
00:06:27.170 --> 00:06:31.130
cancer, not in the adjacent IPMN, and SMAD4 or TGF-beta

115
00:06:31.170 --> 00:06:34.450
receptor II. This makes a lot of sense with what we know about that pathway.

116
00:06:34.950 --> 00:06:38.810
There's an example shown here where the IPMN and the cancer shared a mutation in

117
00:06:38.830 --> 00:06:41.230
KRAS. They shared a mutation in p53.

118
00:06:41.310 --> 00:06:45.250
They shared a mutation in p16. But the SMAD4 nonsense mutation was only

119
00:06:45.270 --> 00:06:45.890
in the cancer.

120
00:06:47.930 --> 00:06:51.840
So again, about a quarter of the cases had a cancer-specific mutation in something

121
00:06:51.850 --> 00:06:54.770
in either SMAD4 or TGF-beta receptor II.

122
00:06:54.790 --> 00:06:58.260
But I think the flip side of that is equally, if not more interesting, which is

123
00:06:58.270 --> 00:07:01.530
that most of the time there's not an obvious genetic alteration that drives

124
00:07:01.570 --> 00:07:04.910
malignant progression. And I think this raises the question of if it's not a

125
00:07:04.970 --> 00:07:07.690
genetic alteration, what could it be?

126
00:07:09.230 --> 00:07:11.670
So we wanted to look in detail at the tumor microenvironment

127
00:07:12.630 --> 00:07:14.200
and how it's altered with malignant progression.

128
00:07:14.530 --> 00:07:17.330
So we took 12 patients who had IPMNs and small invasive

129
00:07:17.350 --> 00:07:21.190
carcinomas. We did comprehensive genomic analyses of these cases

130
00:07:21.250 --> 00:07:24.750
as well, but the data I want to show is from imaging mass cytometry that we did in

131
00:07:24.770 --> 00:07:28.410
collaboration with Wan Jin Ho using a 38-plex TME focus panel.

132
00:07:28.940 --> 00:07:32.670
We quantitatively defined regions of interest in the cancer, the

133
00:07:32.710 --> 00:07:35.650
IPMN, and then what we called the transition zone, where it was a mixture of the

134
00:07:35.710 --> 00:07:36.510
two.

135
00:07:39.570 --> 00:07:43.000
We compared the densities and other quantitative metrics of all the different cells

136
00:07:43.010 --> 00:07:46.400
in the microenvironment. But what turned out to be the most interesting or the most

137
00:07:46.410 --> 00:07:49.470
different between the IPMN and the cancer were the fibroblast populations.

138
00:07:50.130 --> 00:07:53.950
We saw that there were some fibroblast populations, like these indicated in yellow

139
00:07:53.990 --> 00:07:57.440
and green, that were expanded in the invasive cancer,

140
00:07:57.990 --> 00:08:01.810
and then other fibroblast populations, like the green and orange here, that

141
00:08:01.830 --> 00:08:04.750
were decreased in the invasive cancer and expanded in the IPMN.

142
00:08:07.070 --> 00:08:10.710
Again, we quantified this. This is looking at density and showed that some

143
00:08:10.750 --> 00:08:12.170
fibroblast populations are

144
00:08:13.130 --> 00:08:15.510
low in the IPMN, expanded in the cancer.

145
00:08:16.110 --> 00:08:19.940
Other fibroblast populations are high in the IPMN and

146
00:08:19.970 --> 00:08:22.830
then diminished in the invasive cancer.

147
00:08:24.550 --> 00:08:28.080
When we looked in more detail at this imaging mass cytometry data, we saw that

148
00:08:28.110 --> 00:08:30.910
these fibroblast populations occupied distinct spatial niches.

149
00:08:31.010 --> 00:08:34.510
So the H&amp;Es I'm showing here are from those transition zones where you have

150
00:08:34.591 --> 00:08:38.530
IPMN and invasive carcinoma in the same small region, showing that

151
00:08:38.550 --> 00:08:41.951
there's some fibroblast populations that are really right around the IPMN

152
00:08:43.451 --> 00:08:46.930
and not in the cancer, and then other populations that are more in the cancer

153
00:08:47.470 --> 00:08:48.630
and not in the IPMN.

154
00:08:49.550 --> 00:08:52.730
When we were looking through this data, we saw that the immune populations in these

155
00:08:52.810 --> 00:08:56.630
niches were also distinct. So Jesse, who is the PhD

156
00:08:56.670 --> 00:09:00.350
student leading this, worked with Wan Jin Ho to develop a way to quantify

157
00:09:00.630 --> 00:09:02.830
the immune cells that were in these fibroblast niches.

158
00:09:02.870 --> 00:09:06.570
They developed this approach called Clover Patch, which is in press now,

159
00:09:06.730 --> 00:09:07.370
very excitingly.

160
00:09:08.430 --> 00:09:09.810
But what it allows you to do is to,

161
00:09:10.850 --> 00:09:14.530
in an automated way, annotate fibroblast

162
00:09:14.570 --> 00:09:17.630
neighborhoods and then quantify the other cell types within them.

163
00:09:18.790 --> 00:09:22.690
And what we saw is in the cancer-specific fibroblast TMEs, there were

164
00:09:22.750 --> 00:09:26.410
fewer T cells, but also differences in the types of T cells that were there.

165
00:09:26.870 --> 00:09:29.490
And with the IPMN-specific TMEs, we saw a lot more

166
00:09:30.850 --> 00:09:33.940
granzyme positive cytotoxic T cells as well as memory T cells.

167
00:09:34.430 --> 00:09:37.280
And we're still really working through all of the quantification of this data,

168
00:09:38.150 --> 00:09:39.600
so stay tuned for when that's done.

169
00:09:41.640 --> 00:09:45.480
The ultimate goal of this, though, is to do really an integrated analysis, not just

170
00:09:45.490 --> 00:09:49.380
the TME or just the genomics, but to have the set of samples that are really

171
00:09:49.450 --> 00:09:53.270
deeply characterized with respect to their genomic alterations as well as the

172
00:09:53.310 --> 00:09:53.720
TME.

173
00:09:57.590 --> 00:10:01.310
So as I mentioned, 90% of pancreatic cancers arise through these microscopic

174
00:10:01.320 --> 00:10:01.810
pannens.

175
00:10:02.610 --> 00:10:04.670
So I want to spend a little bit of time talking about these.

176
00:10:04.730 --> 00:10:08.670
I will say that our stroma-focused work is more limited in the pannen

177
00:10:08.730 --> 00:10:12.550
space, but thankfully we have two other experts on this, so I hope I can set the

178
00:10:12.610 --> 00:10:14.750
stage for them to present their stromal data.

179
00:10:17.170 --> 00:10:19.270
So because of pannen's small size,

180
00:10:20.710 --> 00:10:24.230
we needed to come up with new approaches to really do tissue quantification to

181
00:10:24.290 --> 00:10:27.830
understand how many pannens were present in the normal pancreas,

182
00:10:28.270 --> 00:10:30.310
how big a pannen is, and how they might be connected.

183
00:10:31.650 --> 00:10:35.610
So we worked with Ashley Keman and Dene Wertz to develop this approach called CODA

184
00:10:35.870 --> 00:10:38.870
that allows us to do 3D quantification of pancreatic tissue.

185
00:10:39.170 --> 00:10:42.750
This is showing a three cubic centimeter piece of normal pancreatic tissue.

186
00:10:43.250 --> 00:10:46.890
This is showing different cell types, normal duct in blue and pre-cancer in red.

187
00:10:47.730 --> 00:10:49.130
It's going to zoom in to show you

188
00:10:50.850 --> 00:10:54.530
adding in the periductal collagen, the blood vessels, the islets of

189
00:10:54.570 --> 00:10:58.530
Langerhans, the fat, and the acinar cells.

190
00:10:58.960 --> 00:11:02.230
It's going to zoom in to show you that you get single-cell resolution in these 3D

191
00:11:02.250 --> 00:11:05.870
models, and then it will zoom out to show you that within this about three cubic

192
00:11:05.930 --> 00:11:09.730
centimeters of tissue, we get the precise 3D location of almost a billion

193
00:11:09.810 --> 00:11:13.550
cells. And again, this 3D modeling approach was

194
00:11:13.610 --> 00:11:15.990
developed by Ashley Keman, Dene Wertz, and Peijun Wu.

195
00:11:17.090 --> 00:11:21.050
We applied it to a large cohort of grossly

196
00:11:21.110 --> 00:11:23.930
normal pancreas from pancreatic surgery resections.

197
00:11:23.950 --> 00:11:27.850
And what we were really struck by with these first few models we did was

198
00:11:27.870 --> 00:11:29.610
that there was a lot of pre-cancer.

199
00:11:29.650 --> 00:11:30.950
So we wanted to investigate

200
00:11:32.030 --> 00:11:34.950
whether these pre-cancers were one large pre-cancer or spread throughout the

201
00:11:34.990 --> 00:11:35.510
pancreas.

202
00:11:37.590 --> 00:11:40.990
This next video is going through the 3D image stack that we used to build the 3D

203
00:11:41.050 --> 00:11:44.530
model, and in this, each spatially separate pannen is annotated in a different

204
00:11:44.630 --> 00:11:44.910
color.

205
00:11:45.970 --> 00:11:48.950
And what I hope you can see in this is that there's lots of different colors here.

206
00:11:48.990 --> 00:11:52.590
There's many different pannens. It's then going to show you the 3D model, and what

207
00:11:52.610 --> 00:11:56.440
you'll see is the tissue falls away with normal duct in blue, and every other

208
00:11:56.530 --> 00:12:00.210
color is a spatially separate pannen. But simply, there's a lot of pannens in here.

209
00:12:00.270 --> 00:12:03.910
There's more than 10 spatially separate pannens in this three cubic

210
00:12:03.950 --> 00:12:07.750
centimeter piece of pancreas.It also really

211
00:12:07.760 --> 00:12:11.610
shows you the level of anatomical and molecular detail you get in these 3D

212
00:12:11.630 --> 00:12:13.070
models. We can really understand

213
00:12:14.270 --> 00:12:17.270
where these PANMs are, how they involve the ductal system, and I think there's a

214
00:12:17.330 --> 00:12:21.250
huge opportunity with these models to understand the environment around

215
00:12:21.270 --> 00:12:22.110
the PANMs as well.

216
00:12:25.870 --> 00:12:29.610
So this CODA approach, which is the 3D modeling approach developed by Denis Ashley

217
00:12:29.630 --> 00:12:33.289
and Pei Xu, lets us do characterization of PANAM size, connectivity, and

218
00:12:33.310 --> 00:12:37.150
number. We then scaled it up. We modeled

219
00:12:38.030 --> 00:12:40.430
exactly 45

220
00:12:41.370 --> 00:12:43.150
blocks of grossly normal pancreatic tissue.

221
00:12:43.190 --> 00:12:45.890
This is showing some examples of the blocks that we analyzed.

222
00:12:46.290 --> 00:12:49.790
I do want to emphasize these were adjacent normal from surgical

223
00:12:49.830 --> 00:12:52.870
resections. A third of the cohort had pancreatic cancer.

224
00:12:52.930 --> 00:12:55.230
The other two-thirds were having a resection for another reason.

225
00:12:56.190 --> 00:12:58.979
But it's not truly normal, which is what we'll hear about, I think, from the next

226
00:12:59.030 --> 00:13:02.990
speaker. In all of these, normal duct is blue, and every other color is a

227
00:13:03.050 --> 00:13:06.250
spatially separate PANAM. So what I hope you can take from this is that,

228
00:13:07.390 --> 00:13:11.129
number one, all of the blocks we modeled had multiple PANMs within a relatively

229
00:13:11.170 --> 00:13:14.730
small sample of pancreas, but there is a fair bit of variability patient to

230
00:13:14.830 --> 00:13:16.830
patient on the number and size of the PANMs.

231
00:13:19.110 --> 00:13:22.150
We looked at how the amount of PANAM correlated with the amount of other tissue

232
00:13:22.190 --> 00:13:25.870
within a block. This is maybe one of the more stromal relevant PANAM

233
00:13:25.890 --> 00:13:27.350
observations in this data set

234
00:13:28.270 --> 00:13:31.370
because we saw that the amount of PANAM within a tissue block was directly

235
00:13:31.410 --> 00:13:34.550
correlated to the amount of collagen or ECM in the block.

236
00:13:35.410 --> 00:13:38.010
We saw it was inversely correlated to the amount of acinar cells.

237
00:13:38.270 --> 00:13:42.130
So what this suggests to us is having PANAM is associated with having fibrosis and

238
00:13:42.230 --> 00:13:44.350
having atrophy of the acinar cells.

239
00:13:45.350 --> 00:13:45.690
Excuse me.

240
00:13:46.570 --> 00:13:50.090
But I think one of the challenges with these observational data sets in human

241
00:13:50.110 --> 00:13:53.010
tissue is you don't know the direction of the causation here.

242
00:13:53.330 --> 00:13:57.170
It could be that inflammation predisposes to PANAM and also

243
00:13:57.190 --> 00:14:01.130
predisposes to atrophy and fibrosis, or it could be that the PANAM obstructs

244
00:14:01.150 --> 00:14:04.070
the ductal system and directly causes the atrophy and fibrosis.

245
00:14:06.110 --> 00:14:10.040
We wanted to come up with a kind of intuitive metric of PANAM burden, and

246
00:14:10.070 --> 00:14:13.530
what we came up with was simply to count the PANMs per cubic centimeter of tissue.

247
00:14:13.590 --> 00:14:13.990
We thought this

248
00:14:14.870 --> 00:14:17.050
made sense with how we were thinking about them.

249
00:14:17.590 --> 00:14:21.430
And what we found was that the mean PANAM burden in our cohort was 13

250
00:14:21.490 --> 00:14:23.130
PANMs per cubic centimeter of tissue.

251
00:14:23.630 --> 00:14:27.090
And if you can visualize how big a cubic centimeter is, it's not very big.

252
00:14:27.630 --> 00:14:31.579
So to have 13 spatially separate precancers in such a small area, to us, was

253
00:14:31.610 --> 00:14:32.290
quite striking.

254
00:14:34.430 --> 00:14:35.380
We then calculated

255
00:14:36.730 --> 00:14:40.330
the mean number of PANMs in the entire pancreas based on that PANAM burden and got

256
00:14:40.390 --> 00:14:41.350
about 1,000.

257
00:14:42.490 --> 00:14:46.139
This is a very noisy estimate for reasons we can discuss in the Q&amp;A, but I think

258
00:14:46.170 --> 00:14:48.450
it's still orders of magnitude more than we were expecting.

259
00:14:50.790 --> 00:14:54.570
We then came up with an approach to do 3D genomic analysis of the PANMs.

260
00:14:54.630 --> 00:14:58.050
We did laser capture microdissection and integrated that in with the 3D models.

261
00:14:58.470 --> 00:14:59.830
I'm not going to show you this in great detail.

262
00:14:59.850 --> 00:15:03.750
It is published, but I'll go over the broad strokes of the

263
00:15:03.770 --> 00:15:07.579
results. We found that almost all of the PANMs we sequenced had

264
00:15:07.610 --> 00:15:11.590
KRAS hotspot mutations. The hotspot mutations occurred in the same distribution

265
00:15:11.630 --> 00:15:15.430
as you see in advanced PDAC, selecting that these KRAS mutations are selected at

266
00:15:15.470 --> 00:15:19.460
PANAM initiation. Like in IPMNs, we found

267
00:15:19.490 --> 00:15:22.910
that when there were multifocal PANMs, they were independent neoplasms that didn't

268
00:15:22.950 --> 00:15:26.510
share any somatic mutations. And we found that, again like IPMNs,

269
00:15:26.950 --> 00:15:28.970
large PANMs can have a polyclonal origin.

270
00:15:31.270 --> 00:15:33.090
Much of our data was focused on point mutations.

271
00:15:33.130 --> 00:15:36.210
We did also look at copy number, and we found that aneuploidy and

272
00:15:37.610 --> 00:15:40.910
extensive copy number alterations was rare in PANMs, even in high grade.

273
00:15:43.310 --> 00:15:47.190
Ashley Keman in collaboration with us, but Ashley was the one

274
00:15:47.210 --> 00:15:50.090
that led this part of the study. She wanted to come up with a way to measure the

275
00:15:50.150 --> 00:15:53.370
inflammation in the PANMs. This was focused on CD45

276
00:15:53.410 --> 00:15:57.380
positive inflammatory cells. I think similar approaches can be used

277
00:15:57.390 --> 00:16:01.190
to measure stroma. But what we were really struck with when we did this

278
00:16:01.210 --> 00:16:04.710
3D quantification of the immune microenvironment was how

279
00:16:04.770 --> 00:16:07.510
heterogeneous it was even within one PANAM.

280
00:16:08.170 --> 00:16:10.850
So this is one spatially contiguous PANAM.

281
00:16:10.930 --> 00:16:14.240
The images on the left and the right are both different regions of that same PANAM,

282
00:16:14.370 --> 00:16:16.530
and you can see on the left there's very little inflammation.

283
00:16:17.070 --> 00:16:18.770
On the right, there's a ton of inflammation.

284
00:16:19.190 --> 00:16:23.109
So the immune and stromal response to these lesions is very

285
00:16:23.130 --> 00:16:25.489
heterogeneous, even within one contiguous PANAM.

286
00:16:27.270 --> 00:16:29.310
And I think this is important for a couple of reasons.

287
00:16:29.370 --> 00:16:31.670
First, the heterogeneity of the PANAM inflammation.

288
00:16:32.890 --> 00:16:36.210
It raises the question of what are the biological drivers of this heterogeneity?

289
00:16:36.690 --> 00:16:39.730
Why is one region of the PANAM so inflamed while other regions are not?

290
00:16:40.430 --> 00:16:44.330
It also impacts the study design as we think about how do we want

291
00:16:44.350 --> 00:16:48.170
to study the microenvironment in these human tissues, because you would get a

292
00:16:48.210 --> 00:16:51.790
very different answer if you were to apply a highly multiplex technology,

293
00:16:52.210 --> 00:16:54.330
depending on which section you chose to apply it to.

294
00:16:57.350 --> 00:16:58.689
So with this, I want to summarize.

295
00:16:59.970 --> 00:17:03.350
I hope I've shown you that pancreatic precancers, both IPMNs and PANMs, are

296
00:17:03.390 --> 00:17:04.080
multifocal.

297
00:17:05.470 --> 00:17:08.999
The progression of these can be driven by somatic mutations, but often it seems not

298
00:17:09.030 --> 00:17:12.530
to be. And I want to raise the question, especially in this session, of whether

299
00:17:12.550 --> 00:17:15.690
microenvironmental features could be an alternative driver of progression in some

300
00:17:15.730 --> 00:17:16.210
lesions.

301
00:17:17.810 --> 00:17:21.050
We've shown using detailed analysis of imaging mass cytometry that

302
00:17:21.171 --> 00:17:24.790
fibroblast populations are distinct between cancer and pre-cancer regions in

303
00:17:24.850 --> 00:17:25.460
IPMNs.

304
00:17:26.510 --> 00:17:29.170
We haven't shown the relevance of this to PANMs, but I think we'll hear

305
00:17:30.970 --> 00:17:33.690
our next speakers talk more about the stroma around the PANMs.

306
00:17:34.810 --> 00:17:37.610
And then finally, I think a note of caution is that the microenvironment is

307
00:17:37.650 --> 00:17:40.410
heterogeneous even over short distances around these precancers.

308
00:17:40.470 --> 00:17:43.170
So we need to think about this with study design and interpretation.

309
00:17:45.330 --> 00:17:48.990
So the overall concept of this session was focused around interception.

310
00:17:49.050 --> 00:17:52.030
So I wanted to close by thinking about what these results might mean for

311
00:17:52.070 --> 00:17:55.890
interception. I think low-grade precancers, both IPMNs and PANMs, are

312
00:17:55.930 --> 00:17:58.210
incredibly common, but they almost never progress.

313
00:17:58.830 --> 00:18:01.270
Again, a very rough calculation just to be provocative.

314
00:18:01.320 --> 00:18:04.090
It's about 1 in 5 million PANMs progress to PDAC.

315
00:18:04.790 --> 00:18:08.509
So with this in mind, if surgery is our intervention, we can't be targeting

316
00:18:08.550 --> 00:18:10.069
low-grade PANAM because

317
00:18:10.890 --> 00:18:12.190
none of us would have a pancreas anymore.

318
00:18:12.230 --> 00:18:13.750
We'd take them all out because we all have them.

319
00:18:14.310 --> 00:18:17.790
So what we need is really biomarkers that predict risk of progression to PDAC,

320
00:18:18.190 --> 00:18:20.390
not biomarkers that predict the presence of a

321
00:18:20.410 --> 00:18:24.386
PANAM.We've heard a lot at this meeting about

322
00:18:24.396 --> 00:18:28.346
targeting KRAS. I think it's an exciting thing to think about whether we should be

323
00:18:28.386 --> 00:18:30.686
using this KRAS targeting in the prevention setting. Right?

324
00:18:30.766 --> 00:18:32.626
All of these PANNs have KRAS mutations.

325
00:18:33.026 --> 00:18:34.866
Most IPMNs have KRAS mutations.

326
00:18:35.686 --> 00:18:39.146
But I think we can also think about how stromal targeting could also be

327
00:18:39.826 --> 00:18:42.226
applied to enhance the efficacy in interception.

328
00:18:43.886 --> 00:18:46.486
So with that, I want to acknowledge the folks that have done the work, including

329
00:18:46.526 --> 00:18:50.426
members of my own lab, Denis and Ashley, and all of our collaborators and our

330
00:18:50.486 --> 00:18:54.186
funding. And then, Ety, are we doing questions now or are we doing questions after?

331
00:18:54.546 --> 00:18:57.286
Okay. Cool. I'm happy to take questions then. Thank you.

