475
00:26:28.406 --> 00:26:31.815
this long meeting. And it is

476
00:26:32.066 --> 00:26:35.966
particularly great to present after Laura because she introduced a

477
00:26:36.026 --> 00:26:39.986
lot of the key concepts that are going to be relevant to my

478
00:26:40.026 --> 00:26:41.646
talk. I have nothing to disclose.

479
00:26:42.906 --> 00:26:45.106
So Laura already introduced pancreatic cancer.

480
00:26:45.126 --> 00:26:49.046
I'd just like to start from the organ pancreatic cancer comes from, which is

481
00:26:49.086 --> 00:26:53.056
the pancreas. And you can see here in these beautiful images,

482
00:26:53.506 --> 00:26:57.426
the exocrine pancreas, the endocrine pancreas that we cancer people don't think

483
00:26:57.466 --> 00:27:01.406
much about, but it's also there. And the exocrine pancreas

484
00:27:01.426 --> 00:27:05.316
is formed by acinar and ducts. We don't actually know

485
00:27:05.366 --> 00:27:09.246
where pancreatic cancer comes from, but when

486
00:27:09.286 --> 00:27:13.106
you get pancreatic cancer, what always struck me with this disease is

487
00:27:13.166 --> 00:27:17.146
that when you compare the normal pancreas on the left to cancer

488
00:27:17.166 --> 00:27:21.126
on the right, you can see that the epithelium in the cancer

489
00:27:21.166 --> 00:27:24.986
is really a small part of the volume, and there is a

490
00:27:25.086 --> 00:27:29.006
sea of tumor microenvironment that has now replaced

491
00:27:29.026 --> 00:27:32.766
the pancreas parenchyma. And I found that

492
00:27:32.786 --> 00:27:36.366
striking for a long time, and one of the things more recently I've become

493
00:27:36.406 --> 00:27:39.986
interested in is how do you go from here to here?

494
00:27:40.306 --> 00:27:42.166
How does this microenvironment develop?

495
00:27:43.386 --> 00:27:46.806
So Laura already covered this, so I don't need to belabor it,

496
00:27:47.306 --> 00:27:49.846
but she explained how there are two main

497
00:27:50.966 --> 00:27:54.866
precursor lesions that can lead to pancreatic cancer, IPMN

498
00:27:54.946 --> 00:27:58.426
and PanIN, and my talk will only be about

499
00:27:58.586 --> 00:28:00.266
PanIN for today.

500
00:28:02.386 --> 00:28:05.546
So those are the questions that I will be addressing.

501
00:28:06.846 --> 00:28:10.726
How common are or is PanIN or pancreatic

502
00:28:10.746 --> 00:28:14.306
intraepithelial neoplasia

503
00:28:14.606 --> 00:28:18.446
in the normal pancreas, like in completely healthy individuals, all

504
00:28:18.526 --> 00:28:22.076
of us standing or sitting here? What is the transcriptional

505
00:28:22.146 --> 00:28:25.415
landscape? What are the characteristics of the

506
00:28:25.466 --> 00:28:28.926
microenvironment? And of course, can we reverse it?

507
00:28:28.986 --> 00:28:32.966
Which I won't directly address, but it's something that I like to speculate

508
00:28:33.026 --> 00:28:34.626
about, just like Laura just did.

509
00:28:36.206 --> 00:28:40.105
So this is just a cartoon to summarize normal pancreas.

510
00:28:40.286 --> 00:28:43.665
We are going to call it benign epithelium for the purpose of this talk,

511
00:28:44.206 --> 00:28:45.826
PanIN, and cancer.

512
00:28:47.086 --> 00:28:48.966
So one of the questions is, how

513
00:28:49.046 --> 00:28:52.886
does the evolution progress in human

514
00:28:52.926 --> 00:28:55.346
samples? We know a lot of it from mouse

515
00:28:56.386 --> 00:29:00.306
work, where we are able to reproduce or recapitulate

516
00:29:00.346 --> 00:29:04.086
tumorigenesis, but mice are not human, and the way we induce

517
00:29:04.466 --> 00:29:07.966
carcinogenesis in mice is not exactly how it happens in humans.

518
00:29:08.546 --> 00:29:10.046
And so we thought it was important to

519
00:29:12.486 --> 00:29:16.286
study this in actual human samples, which is normally difficult because the

520
00:29:16.326 --> 00:29:19.606
pancreas is not something you go and take out for no reason.

521
00:29:19.686 --> 00:29:22.146
You also don't biopsy or

522
00:29:23.026 --> 00:29:26.926
sample in any shape or form unless you have a reason to, but you have a reason to,

523
00:29:26.966 --> 00:29:30.906
that person has some sort of disease or suspected disease, and so it's not

524
00:29:30.966 --> 00:29:34.726
actually normal. So a few years ago, my team and

525
00:29:34.966 --> 00:29:38.806
I had the opportunity to collaborate with Gift of Life Michigan

526
00:29:38.886 --> 00:29:41.626
and with our division of transplant surgery.

527
00:29:42.146 --> 00:29:45.646
Gift of Life is our state's organ donor organization.

528
00:29:46.606 --> 00:29:50.266
Michigan is a relatively small state. It has 10 million inhabitants.

529
00:29:50.326 --> 00:29:51.546
It's very rural.

530
00:29:52.826 --> 00:29:56.366
But the one thing we had was that we

531
00:29:56.406 --> 00:30:00.386
do organ procurement in a very different way than any other state

532
00:30:00.506 --> 00:30:02.686
in the US, and I think anywhere in the world.

533
00:30:03.846 --> 00:30:07.806
Donors on life support from the whole state are flown into

534
00:30:07.866 --> 00:30:11.626
a facility on the south side of Ann Arbor, which is a tiny college

535
00:30:11.746 --> 00:30:14.826
town. And so we're able to collect

536
00:30:14.926 --> 00:30:18.526
tissue locally from the whole state, which

537
00:30:18.586 --> 00:30:20.756
is pretty unique. And thanks to that,

538
00:30:21.626 --> 00:30:24.826
this is what happens. We get a call.

539
00:30:25.646 --> 00:30:27.466
Everybody in the lab goes on alert.

540
00:30:27.706 --> 00:30:31.670
We receive-Bucket,

541
00:30:31.890 --> 00:30:35.410
which contains a human pancreas, usually with the spleen and part of the

542
00:30:35.470 --> 00:30:39.110
intestine still attached. And then we have a way we developed to

543
00:30:39.170 --> 00:30:43.150
dissect it and create samples for a whole lot of uses, some of which are

544
00:30:43.170 --> 00:30:47.070
described here. Relevant for today, we do single-cell

545
00:30:47.150 --> 00:30:50.610
RNA sequencing. We take blocks for histology immunohistochemistry.

546
00:30:51.070 --> 00:30:54.870
We also store blood, and we also make organoids, although I

547
00:30:54.930 --> 00:30:56.250
won't be talking about those.

548
00:30:57.590 --> 00:31:00.610
So why am I going into all these details?

549
00:31:00.650 --> 00:31:01.110
Well, because the

550
00:31:02.530 --> 00:31:06.050
function of the pancreas is to produce digestive enzymes, and so

551
00:31:06.930 --> 00:31:10.710
when the pancreas is out of the body or when the person is

552
00:31:10.730 --> 00:31:14.470
deceased, the enzymes get released from acinar cells, and they essentially start

553
00:31:14.530 --> 00:31:18.330
digesting the tissue. And so if there is warm ischemia, and

554
00:31:18.370 --> 00:31:22.350
that's the case of this set of donors here, viability is really

555
00:31:22.370 --> 00:31:22.650
low.

556
00:31:24.130 --> 00:31:28.070
So we only take donors where there is no warm ischemia, and we're able to get

557
00:31:28.170 --> 00:31:32.070
very high cell viability, very intact tissue, which is really important when

558
00:31:32.110 --> 00:31:35.789
you want to study the morphology, transcriptome, and other things like

559
00:31:35.830 --> 00:31:36.130
that.

560
00:31:36.950 --> 00:31:40.870
And so we're at about 160 donors now, but that's

561
00:31:40.890 --> 00:31:44.530
the breakdown, which hasn't really changed as we update those

562
00:31:45.050 --> 00:31:48.850
graphs. So we have about two-thirds male donors, one-third

563
00:31:48.950 --> 00:31:52.890
female, two-thirds white, and one-third Black donors.

564
00:31:53.690 --> 00:31:57.600
Importantly, our donors come from a wide range of ages, and

565
00:31:57.630 --> 00:32:01.350
so that's been the other limitation in the field to be able to study the

566
00:32:01.370 --> 00:32:04.770
pancreas in young individuals. And to a question that was asked before,

567
00:32:05.390 --> 00:32:09.130
most surgical samples come from individuals that tend to be somewhat older.

568
00:32:10.010 --> 00:32:13.670
So when we got the pancreas, we started doing histology,

569
00:32:13.820 --> 00:32:15.750
and we realized that

570
00:32:16.670 --> 00:32:20.270
many of them contain panin lesions. And I'm just showing you examples.

571
00:32:20.410 --> 00:32:24.250
Each one of the pictures is from a different organ in a

572
00:32:24.310 --> 00:32:25.210
different donor.

573
00:32:26.130 --> 00:32:28.070
More pictures here. So

574
00:32:29.130 --> 00:32:30.590
that's not what we were expecting.

575
00:32:30.710 --> 00:32:33.890
That was before Laura's paper was out, and so we

576
00:32:34.670 --> 00:32:38.410
started doing a very rough quantification, and we realized that

577
00:32:38.850 --> 00:32:42.050
well more than half, and this is probably an underestimate, but

578
00:32:43.050 --> 00:32:46.780
more than half of donors, even in fairly young ages, have panin

579
00:32:46.910 --> 00:32:47.430
lesions.

580
00:32:49.350 --> 00:32:53.220
So okay, if we all have lesions but most of us don't

581
00:32:53.250 --> 00:32:56.010
get pancreatic cancer, why is that?

582
00:32:56.070 --> 00:32:59.590
And one way to think about it, and this is something actually

583
00:32:59.890 --> 00:33:03.730
Laura and I, together with Claus Jørgensen from Cancer UK Manchester,

584
00:33:03.810 --> 00:33:07.470
have thought a lot about, and that's our working model for which we have zero

585
00:33:07.590 --> 00:33:11.190
proof. But the idea is that the panin are not all

586
00:33:11.230 --> 00:33:15.210
created equal. We do have proof they're quite heterogeneous, and some might

587
00:33:15.290 --> 00:33:16.790
progress and some might not.

588
00:33:18.330 --> 00:33:18.910
But

589
00:33:19.910 --> 00:33:23.379
refocusing on the panin, the first thing we have to do is really understand what

590
00:33:23.410 --> 00:33:26.810
they look like and what their characteristics are in

591
00:33:26.850 --> 00:33:30.530
humans. So I'll start from the epithelium

592
00:33:30.650 --> 00:33:34.610
component because even though this is a microenvironment section, obviously

593
00:33:34.650 --> 00:33:38.630
everything starts from the epithelium being altered, KRAS mutations, that's

594
00:33:38.650 --> 00:33:42.530
the initiating insult. And I'm going to show you work that

595
00:33:42.570 --> 00:33:46.210
was largely done by Ahmed Elhosseiny, a bioinformatics

596
00:33:46.290 --> 00:33:49.830
graduate student who recently graduated and left my lab and is doing a

597
00:33:49.870 --> 00:33:53.570
postdoc at Memorial Sloan Kettering, and Jude Okoye, who is a

598
00:33:53.590 --> 00:33:56.930
postdoc from Nigeria. Jude has done all the

599
00:33:56.950 --> 00:34:00.010
immunostainings you will see, and Ahmed all the bioinformatics.

600
00:34:00.670 --> 00:34:04.480
And also, I should mention, this is a collaborative effort with my colleagues Tim

601
00:34:04.590 --> 00:34:08.250
Frankel and Nadine Carpenter, and with Ilana Fertig at the University of

602
00:34:08.310 --> 00:34:08.750
Maryland.

603
00:34:10.410 --> 00:34:14.310
So okay, the challenge is, even though almost everybody has panin,

604
00:34:14.870 --> 00:34:16.730
most of the pancreas is still normal.

605
00:34:16.810 --> 00:34:20.330
And so you have this small lesion in a sea of normal acini.

606
00:34:20.910 --> 00:34:23.730
So how can you really characterize it?

607
00:34:23.790 --> 00:34:26.910
And so we decided to use spatial transcriptomics, and we

608
00:34:27.670 --> 00:34:30.111
utilized initially the 10x Visium

609
00:34:30.470 --> 00:34:32.690
platform. So

610
00:34:33.690 --> 00:34:37.511
with this method, you end up with a little circle

611
00:34:37.770 --> 00:34:41.710
where you sequence the RNA. And so it's sort of like bulk RNA sequencing,

612
00:34:42.310 --> 00:34:46.051
except you have a lot of really tiny samples per each slide.

613
00:34:46.830 --> 00:34:48.770
And that's what it actually looks like.

614
00:34:48.810 --> 00:34:51.720
So each of these dots is an area that was sequenced.

615
00:34:51.790 --> 00:34:55.630
You can also see we lose some transcripts, but the areas that are sequenced

616
00:34:55.730 --> 00:34:56.290
are either

617
00:34:57.690 --> 00:35:01.220
pretty uniform or pretty heterogeneous in terms of the cells they

618
00:35:01.220 --> 00:35:01.810
contain.

619
00:35:02.870 --> 00:35:06.770
So we had to develop a framework to analyze it, and I'm going to

620
00:35:06.790 --> 00:35:09.670
go kind of fast, but I'm happy to ask questions.

621
00:35:10.950 --> 00:35:14.410
So the idea is that we have single-cell RNA sequencing and spatial

622
00:35:14.450 --> 00:35:18.400
transcriptomics from the very same samples, and that allows us to do

623
00:35:18.430 --> 00:35:22.210
two different things. To look at each domain just based on it

624
00:35:22.310 --> 00:35:26.050
being a spatial domain in sort of a cell-agnostic manner,

625
00:35:26.230 --> 00:35:29.570
but also do the convolution and then see what do the

626
00:35:31.230 --> 00:35:35.170
epithelial or fibroblasts or immune cells do,

627
00:35:35.210 --> 00:35:37.010
or what are they like in that domain.

628
00:35:38.290 --> 00:35:42.250
And so that's an example. Those are spatial domains in healthy pancreas in

629
00:35:42.270 --> 00:35:45.710
a tumor. Right now, they're just color-coded based on the

630
00:35:45.750 --> 00:35:49.370
transcripts they have, so it's cell agnostic, but then we

631
00:35:49.450 --> 00:35:49.950
can

632
00:35:51.110 --> 00:35:54.850
refer them back to single-cell RNA sequencing from the same samples.

633
00:35:54.970 --> 00:35:58.930
Now we know which type of cell has what transcripts, and that

634
00:35:58.970 --> 00:36:02.870
allows us to do the convolution, which then allows us to give

635
00:36:02.910 --> 00:36:06.670
names to domains. And so we end up with a number

636
00:36:06.750 --> 00:36:09.890
of types of domains. Some are, for example, only acinar.

637
00:36:09.970 --> 00:36:13.810
Some have fibroblasts are sort of everywhere because that's what fibroblasts

638
00:36:13.850 --> 00:36:16.890
do. They're close to other cells and so on and so forth.

639
00:36:17.830 --> 00:36:21.770
And so essentially, you go from something

640
00:36:21.830 --> 00:36:25.770
like this with all the colors and domains numbered one to 17,

641
00:36:26.390 --> 00:36:30.190
to something like this, where now those domains have names based on the

642
00:36:30.230 --> 00:36:31.690
cells that are populating

643
00:36:31.730 --> 00:36:35.334
them.Okay. And then if you look

644
00:36:35.394 --> 00:36:39.214
across all the samples, you can see that in the normal pancreas you have a

645
00:36:39.254 --> 00:36:43.234
lot of red, which is an acinar domain, because the normal

646
00:36:43.244 --> 00:36:47.074
pancreas has mostly acini. But the tumors are very colorful

647
00:36:47.134 --> 00:36:50.674
because the tumors are very heterogeneous, and they have a lot of different types

648
00:36:50.734 --> 00:36:52.594
of cells/domains in them.

649
00:36:53.734 --> 00:36:57.274
Okay. So once you get there, you can start comparing.

650
00:36:57.314 --> 00:37:00.814
And so the one very simple comparison is

651
00:37:01.234 --> 00:37:03.554
looking at prevalence of certain types of cells.

652
00:37:03.614 --> 00:37:07.454
And so tumors have more macrophages, they have

653
00:37:08.274 --> 00:37:12.154
more of other immune cells. They lose acinar cells, so acinar

654
00:37:12.214 --> 00:37:16.054
cells are more common in healthy. And then you can see

655
00:37:16.134 --> 00:37:19.334
when you look at the fibroblasts, which are one of my favorite cell types, you

656
00:37:19.394 --> 00:37:23.094
start seeing a tail on each end. That's because

657
00:37:23.104 --> 00:37:27.034
some fibroblasts are more common in normal, while others

658
00:37:27.054 --> 00:37:31.014
are more common in tumor. But if we do things this way, we sort of are

659
00:37:31.134 --> 00:37:32.914
not using the spatial information.

660
00:37:32.954 --> 00:37:36.814
We did all that work and spent all that money to get spatial data, and now we

661
00:37:36.834 --> 00:37:40.314
are treating it like single cell. So we didn't want to do that.

662
00:37:41.014 --> 00:37:41.194
So,

663
00:37:43.774 --> 00:37:47.374
the way we went about it is, first of all, going back to the

664
00:37:47.394 --> 00:37:50.834
domains, we can map the domains that contain the epithelial

665
00:37:50.894 --> 00:37:54.414
transcripts, and that gives us an idea

666
00:37:54.774 --> 00:37:58.294
that things are a little more complicated than we thought.

667
00:37:58.334 --> 00:38:02.234
So when we look at all the benign domains, they're all in adjacent

668
00:38:02.914 --> 00:38:06.534
red and green and blue here are acinar domains.

669
00:38:06.554 --> 00:38:10.294
The ductals are in purple, are clearly separate, but the neoplastic

670
00:38:10.334 --> 00:38:13.234
domains are almost their own thing. They're completely separate.

671
00:38:14.674 --> 00:38:18.274
And so if we now take the neoplastic domains

672
00:38:18.534 --> 00:38:22.494
only and we put them together, what you're seeing is a couple of things.

673
00:38:22.714 --> 00:38:24.344
First of all, they're contiguous.

674
00:38:24.934 --> 00:38:28.754
The pannexin that come from either adjacent normal or donor

675
00:38:29.334 --> 00:38:33.214
are all in one area. And then you have glandular tumor, and then

676
00:38:33.274 --> 00:38:35.554
you have poorly differentiated tumor in pink.

677
00:38:35.914 --> 00:38:38.014
But if you look carefully, there are a few

678
00:38:39.214 --> 00:38:42.844
donor pannexin that are actually quite far into

679
00:38:42.894 --> 00:38:46.754
the tumor area. So you start getting the idea that things

680
00:38:46.794 --> 00:38:50.514
are not quite as simple and not all pannexin are created

681
00:38:50.574 --> 00:38:50.874
equal.

682
00:38:52.894 --> 00:38:56.734
So the other thing is that if we do this analysis using domains,

683
00:38:56.814 --> 00:39:00.634
we then want to know are the differences really driven by transcripts in

684
00:39:00.674 --> 00:39:04.654
epithelial cells? And we can do then deconvolution and look only at

685
00:39:04.934 --> 00:39:08.614
epithelial transcripts. So we go from something like this to only

686
00:39:08.674 --> 00:39:10.014
looking at epithelial transcripts.

687
00:39:10.164 --> 00:39:13.734
And now we can see, first of all, they still fall in

688
00:39:13.774 --> 00:39:17.234
groups that correspond to the samples, to the

689
00:39:17.274 --> 00:39:20.794
histology they came from. But also we can

690
00:39:20.834 --> 00:39:23.214
compare and do differences. And so,

691
00:39:24.574 --> 00:39:27.714
I will only show you one thing because we don't have much time.

692
00:39:28.294 --> 00:39:29.354
One of the differences

693
00:39:31.114 --> 00:39:34.954
was IL6/JAK-STAT3 signaling, which is highly enriched in

694
00:39:35.034 --> 00:39:38.854
poorly differentiated tumors. So that's something we could easily validate,

695
00:39:39.874 --> 00:39:42.174
which Jude did by immunostaining.

696
00:39:42.234 --> 00:39:43.214
This is showing

697
00:39:44.534 --> 00:39:47.514
pannexin where you do not see phospho-STAT3,

698
00:39:48.694 --> 00:39:52.254
a well-differentiated tumor and then poorly

699
00:39:52.294 --> 00:39:56.034
differentiated tumor. And if I use high mag, you can clearly

700
00:39:56.094 --> 00:39:59.234
see that in pannexin if you have phospho-STAT3, it's usually in the

701
00:39:59.274 --> 00:40:01.294
microenvironment where it is also found.

702
00:40:01.734 --> 00:40:04.634
In tumors, you have a lot of nuclear phospho-STAT3.

703
00:40:06.174 --> 00:40:09.554
So okay, that's great. That tells us that pannexin have some of tumor

704
00:40:09.574 --> 00:40:12.254
characteristics. They are continuous, but they're different.

705
00:40:13.154 --> 00:40:17.104
They haven't acquired higher regulation of STAT3 and other pathways

706
00:40:17.194 --> 00:40:19.654
which I didn't have time to go into.

707
00:40:19.734 --> 00:40:21.714
But what about the microenvironment?

708
00:40:21.954 --> 00:40:25.754
And that's when we really needed to be able to use the spatial information.

709
00:40:25.934 --> 00:40:29.894
And so we decided to use neighborhood

710
00:40:29.954 --> 00:40:33.244
analysis where histology and

711
00:40:33.334 --> 00:40:36.634
transcriptomics allowed us to identify different

712
00:40:36.754 --> 00:40:40.574
structures. And the structures I'm showing you here are ducts, which are really

713
00:40:40.594 --> 00:40:44.394
nice because there are normal ducts in both healthy samples and

714
00:40:44.434 --> 00:40:46.974
in tumor samples, so they are almost an internal control.

715
00:40:47.614 --> 00:40:48.884
And then we have

716
00:40:50.113 --> 00:40:53.613
a pannexin in the donor samples. And then GL tumors stands for

717
00:40:53.654 --> 00:40:57.454
glandular tumor, which is kind of the same as well differentiated and then poorly

